594
00:52:13,762 --> 00:52:19,245
Car Park is currently one of two ramp structures in the city.

595
00:52:19,986 --> 00:52:24,288
And I want to give a little bit of background into the ADA and playgrounds because it's a little confusing.

596
00:52:25,576 --> 00:52:31,079
First, the ADA, when it was formed, did not have any guidelines about how that was going to apply in playgrounds.

597
00:52:31,139 --> 00:52:32,020
And that didn't happen until 2010.

598
00:52:32,360 --> 00:52:35,502
So it was very far into the process.

599
00:52:36,303 --> 00:52:50,232
And in that room of people deciding how the ADA was going to apply in play settings, it was very much a compromised document, which means it is not maybe as inclusive as we would like it to be.

600
00:52:51,913 --> 00:52:53,354
So things like each,

601
00:52:54,508 --> 00:53:06,056
Each slide, climber, like spinny thing, whatever it's attached, whether it's a play panel, it's got a steering wheel, each one of those is called an elevated play component.

602
00:53:07,077 --> 00:53:20,646
And the rule that they came up with as a group was that if a structure, a climbing structure, has 20 or more elevated play components, then half of it has to be accessible.

603
00:53:23,856 --> 00:53:30,360
like 25% has to be via ramp and 25% has to be via transfer platform.

604
00:53:30,400 --> 00:53:31,861
This is the bare minimum, right?

605
00:53:31,921 --> 00:53:34,643
The AGA is the floor, not the ceiling, not what we aspire to.

606
00:53:35,963 --> 00:53:44,809
But if a structure has 19 or fewer, then you only have to have a certain number of each type of thing, like each climber, each slide.

607
00:53:45,269 --> 00:53:50,552
Maybe there only has to be one slide that's actually on the accessible route of a playground.

608
00:53:52,303 --> 00:53:58,528
And so a lot of designers make all their playgrounds with 19 or fewer elevated play components so they don't have to put ramps in.

609
00:54:00,289 --> 00:54:01,330
But they're compliant.

610
00:54:02,371 --> 00:54:05,394
I want you to think of the playgrounds that you've seen.

611
00:54:05,434 --> 00:54:16,623
There's often, some of you might already know this, but just to make sure we're all on the same page, you're going to see two steps and then like a big platform on the stairs, and then the steps continue up.

612
00:54:17,364 --> 00:54:18,645
That is the transfer platform.

613
00:54:19,517 --> 00:54:36,440
That is the basis of accessibility for playgrounds, is having somebody who uses a mobility device be able to wheel or walk her up, transfer to the playground, and then scoot around or walk as they're able.

614
00:54:36,860 --> 00:54:43,401
But that's the plan, is to be able to scoot around on your bum all around the playground, or at least until the accessible route ends.

615
00:54:44,582 --> 00:54:46,082
And then you can supposedly reach

616
00:54:47,317 --> 00:54:50,019
the bare minimum number of elements there.

617
00:54:50,820 --> 00:54:51,860
So it's not awesome.

618
00:54:52,361 --> 00:55:04,589
And when you think about the number of people with disabilities, and then you take out all the people who can walk, and all the people who have a visual impairment but don't need a da-da-da-da, we get down to people who use mobility devices.

619
00:55:05,650 --> 00:55:15,397
And then what I was told by one of the leading experts in how the ADA applies in recreation settings is that 3% to 5% of people who use mobility devices can or want to transfer.

620
00:55:16,389 --> 00:55:19,910
So now we have 3-5% of that population that we're designing playgrounds for.

621
00:55:20,070 --> 00:55:20,710
And that's the code.

622
00:55:22,210 --> 00:55:37,014
What I have learned is that there are... The only guideline that has anything to do with visual impairment is how... So the rule is that you have to be able to get to each element and around each element, but you don't have to be able to use it if it's on the ground.

623
00:55:39,393 --> 00:55:45,678
And the route that you take to get to and around has to be eight feet tall so that someone with a visual impairment doesn't hit their heads on anything.

624
00:55:45,698 --> 00:55:46,178
But that's it.

625
00:55:46,799 --> 00:55:50,622
There's no guidelines on contrasting steps or handrails or anything like that.

626
00:55:53,144 --> 00:55:57,727
Surfacing is its own whole thing, and we're not going to get into that right now because it's a bigger discussion.

627
00:55:57,767 --> 00:56:01,990
But the state of Massachusetts is moving toward having all-unitary surfacing.

628
00:56:02,330 --> 00:56:04,512
But it's going to take a long time to get that to turn over.

629
00:56:04,552 --> 00:56:08,255
But there shouldn't be any more mulch in Massachusetts in the next couple of decades.

630
00:56:11,218 --> 00:56:12,800
So, that's like the ADA in playgrounds.

631
00:56:13,921 --> 00:56:22,167
And then the question about how we think about accessibility in playgrounds is accessible for whom, right?

632
00:56:22,387 --> 00:56:27,431
Like, we know as this group that accessibility for one person does not mean accessibility for another.

633
00:56:27,811 --> 00:56:32,475
I was talking to some people from Perkins School for the Blind

634
00:56:33,959 --> 00:56:42,423
about the McGlynn playground and they were saying, they were like, yeah, you know those like two steps on the playground and then they like take a 90 degree turn and they go down the rest of the steps?

635
00:56:42,563 --> 00:56:47,225
Our kids fall off of those all the time because there's no warning that these steps are just going to fall off.

636
00:56:47,245 --> 00:56:49,886
And I said, so the irony of that is that's the transfer platform.

637
00:56:51,246 --> 00:56:54,348
So even the things that we do for one population don't work for others.

638
00:56:55,228 --> 00:56:59,030
And you cannot have one playground be everything to everyone.

639
00:56:59,070 --> 00:56:59,970
It's just not possible.

640
00:57:01,748 --> 00:57:06,931
Autistic children might need more sensory equipment.

641
00:57:06,951 --> 00:57:12,175
They might need a fence because if they get scared, they might not have the awareness to not run out into a street.

642
00:57:12,215 --> 00:57:14,017
But not every playground needs to be fenced.

643
00:57:16,258 --> 00:57:20,401
Accessible swings, we want to make sure that there are things that you can transfer in for your smaller kids.

644
00:57:20,481 --> 00:57:23,163
And then if you don't want to transfer, you also can swing and spin.

645
00:57:26,590 --> 00:57:28,331
All sorts of pieces to this.

646
00:57:28,451 --> 00:57:39,318
And what I want to start helping the city do is take a more broad and systemic look at how we're thinking about accessibility in our playgrounds and the opportunities that are offered.

647
00:57:39,358 --> 00:57:48,344
Because you can have a really delightfully ramped playground, and all that's actually offered is a steering wheel and a tic-tac-toe board.

648
00:57:49,405 --> 00:57:51,646
It doesn't matter if it's ramped if it's not actually fun.

649
00:57:55,126 --> 00:57:56,107
So, that's setting the stage.

650
00:57:56,688 --> 00:58:02,934
So, right now, the City of Medford has 21 playgrounds between the school district and the city-owned sites.

651
00:58:05,297 --> 00:58:11,763
The goal, eventually, is to get to a third of those being really inclusive.

652
00:58:12,264 --> 00:58:15,707
Like, that's kind of the national, you can't, we can't do everything, we can't do everything overnight.

653
00:58:18,588 --> 00:58:25,573
It's not possible, so the goal is to go with a third of the playgrounds that a municipality owns as really inclusive.

654
00:58:28,014 --> 00:58:35,659
Right now, Carr is one of two that have ramps, but the playground is being torn down.

655
00:58:36,680 --> 00:58:48,007
My question to you right now is how do you want to think about where we should be locating inclusive playgrounds in our city?

656
00:58:48,839 --> 00:58:50,099
and prioritizing those.

657
00:58:52,900 --> 00:58:59,682
Car has parking, but it is nowhere near accessible parking or accessible transportation or any transportation at all.

658
00:59:02,683 --> 00:59:09,765
Ramped playgrounds tend to work best in places where you're going to be adding a lot of land, like the McGlynn.

659
00:59:10,206 --> 00:59:12,006
I'm going to pull up an image.

660
00:59:12,906 --> 00:59:17,948
But the McGlynn is going to have a hill that the structure is built into so that

661
00:59:18,499 --> 00:59:26,445
The ramp, we don't have to pay for surfacing under a ramp that takes 12 feet this way for every one foot in elevation height.

662
00:59:27,325 --> 00:59:33,330
It takes a lot of space and a lot of extra funding to do ramps on a playground that don't add any play value.

663
00:59:33,410 --> 00:59:43,957
So adding hill forms makes it a lot more fun and pretty and more cost effective in terms of like what you're paying for to get up high.

664
00:59:47,088 --> 00:59:59,959
